`infinite/` implements the programmatic replay path for `dict.infinite.steno`: instead of enumerating every count-resolved row, it builds compact tables (`InfType`, `Construct`) and reconstructs any lookup on demand by walking the stroke sequence. Depending on this subtree gets `build_tables` (table construction, run once at build time) and `walk` (per-query replay, run at lookup time) — callers never see Pass B enumeration for this path.

The two halves are tightly coupled through shared data structures, not code: `mod.rs` builds `Construct.fill_order` (D12: fuse-target first, else template order) and `walk.rs`'s `walk_construct` consumes slots in exactly that order — changing fill-order logic in one requires updating the other's slot-fill loop. Similarly, `mod.rs`'s `render_type_text` and `walk.rs`'s `render_type`/`consume_type` both interpret `%t` markers and must agree on substitution semantics, or replayed text diverges from built text.

`mod.rs` is the table builder and the sole build-time safety net: `check_fuse_ambiguity` catches fuse collisions that enumeration would otherwise surface as row conflicts, since this path never produces rows to conflict. `walk.rs` is the reference walker (criterion 3) whose "in progress" rendering (`is_bracket`, partial obligations) must mirror `render::non_terminal_text`/`render::is_bracket` and the C++ port in `emit/` exactly — the golden-test header built by `emit/test.rs` is what verifies this walker against the C++ replay, so a rendering change here is invisible until that test runs.

Invariant spanning the subtree: every construct built by `mod.rs` must be walkable to a unique, correct render by `walk.rs` for any valid stroke sequence — enumeration's implicit collision detection is replaced entirely by `check_fuse_ambiguity` plus the golden test, so neither can be skipped when either half changes.